# 1. Annotated Biliography
Nguyen, Anthony, et al. "3.5-D Blocking Optimization for Stencil Computations on Modern CPUs and GPUs." ACM/IEEE International Conference for High PERFORMANCE Computing, Networking, Storage and Analysis IEEE Computer Society, 2010:1-13. \
\
This article present a novel 3.5-dimension blocking algorithm which performs 2.5-dimension spatial and 1-dimension temporal blocking of the input grid in on-chip memory for both CPUs and GPUs. The algorithm is amenable to both TLP and DLP, and scales near-linearly with the SIMD width and multiple-cores. The performance of 7-point stencil and LBM using this algorithm is comparable or better than the fastest reported in the literature for both CPUs and GPUs in 2010.

# 2. Core Content
## 2.1 3.5D Blocking (2.5D Spatial + 1D Temporal)
The objective of this algorithm is to improve the throughput of stencil-based kernels for which the bandwidth-to-compute ratio ($ \gamma $) is greater than the corresponding peak bandwidth to peak compute ratio ($ \Gamma $) of the underlying architecture.

### 2.1.1 Spatial Blocking
#### 2.1.1.1 Wavefront Blocking
A Spatial Blocking techniques are aimed at completely utilizing each data element that is loaded in the on-chip storage. \
For every step ($ s $) on stencil-based kernels, the amount of data required to be resident in the on-chip memory is the set grid points ($ P_{s} $) such that:
```math
(s - R) \leq |P_{s}| \leq (s + R)
```
Where R (Radius) denotes the radius (in units) of extent of the stencil, usually defined as the Manhattan distance or $ L_{\infty} $ norm. \
However, this methodology suffers from two performance concerns:
1. The working set increases as the wave-front approaches the center of the grid.
2. Thread-level parallelism is extracted by evenly distributing the grid points amongst the threads.

#### 2.1.1.2 3D Blocking
A commonly used technique to divide the input into overlapping axis-aligned 3D blocks. \
![3D_Blocking][var-png-base64-3D_Blocking] \
Since the grid elements within distance R of the boundary (termed as ghost layer, overlapped layer) do not satisfy this constraint, the computation is only performed for this number of elements within a block:
```math
(din^{3D}_{X} - 2R) \times (din^{3D}_{Y} - 2R) \times (din^{3D}_{Z} - 2R)
```
Where $ dim^{3D}_{W} $ denotes the length of dimension W. \
Since the complete block needs to reside in the on-chip memory, this requires:
```math
(\xi dim^{3D}_{X} dim^{3D}_{Y} dim^{3D}_{Z}) \leq C
```
Where $ \xi $ denotes the size of each grid element; C (Capacity) denotes then size of the available fast on-chip storage (LLC and registers for CPU, shared memory and registers for GPU). \
As far as the bandwidth is concerned, the elements in the ghost layer are loaded multiple times. The ratio of extra bandwidth required ($ \kappa^{3D} $) is around:
```math
\kappa^{3D} = \frac{1}{(1 - 2R / dim^{3D}_{X})(1 - 2R / dim^{3D}_{Y})(1 - 2R / dim^{3D}_{Z})}
```
To minimize the amount of extra bandwidth (to minimize the result of the formula above), set $ dim^{3D}_{X} $, $ dim^{3D}_{Y} $ and $ dim^{3D}_{Z} $ equal to each other, with each being set to:
```math
\lfloor \sqrt[3]{C / \xi} \rfloor
```
For any specific Z value ($ Z_{s} $), they only require grid elements tithin ($ Z_{s} +/- R $) Z planes to be resident in the cache, a total of 2R+1 planes. **(I don't understand how they figure out the number of total planes to be resident in the cache)**
#### 2.1.1.3 2.5D Spatial Blocking
The previous paragraph exploited the fact that only (2R+1)XY planes need to be cache resident. Therefore, they perform blocking in 2D (XY) plane, and stream through the third dimension (Z). They denote this as 2.5D blocking. For which, each block element size $ \xi $ requires:
```math
(\xi (2R + 1) dim^{2.5D}_{X} dim^{2.5D}_{Y}) \leq C
```
Where $ dim^{2.5D}_{W} $ denotes the length of  W dimension in a 2.5D block. \
They denote the blocking data structure as $ Buffer^{2.5D} $, with dimensions:
```math
(dim^{2.5D}_{X}, dim^{2.5D}_{Y}, 2R+1)
```
$ Buffer^{2.5D} $ should have enough space for (2R+1) XY sub-planes, with the $ i^{th} $ sub-plane, the computation consists of the following 2 phases: \
**Phase 1:** *Prolog* - Load the grid elements for the XY sub-plane with z to [0 .. 2R) into $ Buffer^{2.5D} $[0 .. 2R) respectively. \
**Phase 2:** *Cache-Friendly Stencil Computation* - For each z $ \in $ [R .. $ N_{z} $): \
(a) Load the XY sub-plane for (z+R) into $ Buffer^{2.5D} $[(z+R)%(2R+1)]. \
(b) Perform stencil computation for XY sub-plane stored in $ Buffer^{2.5D} $[z%(2R+1)] and store the result into external memory. \
\
Compared with 3D blocking, there is no extra bandwidth requirement in the Z direction in 2.5D blocking. The total extra bandwidth becomes:
```math
\kappa^{2.5D} = \frac{1}{(1 - 2R / dim^{2.5D}_{X})(1 - 2R / dim^{2.5D}_{Y})}
```
The block dimension length to minimize the extra bandwidth becomes:
```math
dim^{2.5D}_{X} = dim^{2.5D}_{Y} = \lfloor \sqrt[2]{C / (\xi (2R + 1))} \rfloor
```

#### 2.1.1.4 3.5D Computation Flow
Consider the following figure, let $ S_{i} $ denote the $ i^{th} $ step of the execution. $ S_{i} $ at the time instance $ t^{''} $ compute the grid elements for a specific $ z_{s} $ value by reading grid elements from [$ z_{s}-1, z_{s}, z_{s}+1 $] at time instance $ t^{'}-1 $. \
![3.5D buffer management and TLP expoiting][var-png-base64-3.5D_buffer_management_and_TLP_exploiting] \
In the figure (a) above, they set $ dim_{T} $ (temporal dimension) is the time period from t=0 to t=3. Note that only the step executed for t=0 and t=3 read and write data from/to the external memory respectively. Other time steps have no communication with the external memory. The resultant bandwidth reduces by a factor of $ dim_{T} $. \
In order to scale with larger number of computational cores, they store 4 sub-planes instead of storing 3 sub-planes per time instance. This ensures that one step at each time instance can be executed in parallel with each other, including reading and writing data from/to different buffers. By storing 4 XY sub-planes per time instance, these steps can be executed in parallel. Thus $ (dim_{T})(2R+2) $ XY sub-planes need to be maintain in the caches. As far as the size of each XY sub-plane is concerned, since all the buffers need to reside inthe cache, the $ \xi $ requires:
```math
(\xi (2R+2) dim_{T} dim^{3.5D}_{X} dim^{3.5D}_{Y}) \leq C
```
Then the extra bandwidth for 3.5D blocking becomes:
```math
\kappa^{3.5D} = \frac{1}{(1 - 2R \times dim_{T} / dim^{3.5D}_{X})(1 - 2R \times dim_{T} / dim^{3.5D}_{Y})}
```
In order to maximize the use of computational resources, $ dim_{T} $ should be greater than the ratios of the bandwidth-to-compute of the kernel ($ \gamma $) to the peak bandwidth-to-compute of the machine ($ \Gamma $). Hence:
```math
dim_{T} \geq \eta = \lceil \frac{\gamma}{\Gamma} \rceil
```
The block dimension length to minimizing the extra bandwidth becomes:
```math
dim^{3.5D}_{X} = dim^{3.5D}_{Y} = \lfloor \sqrt[2]{C / (\xi (2R + 2) \eta)} \rfloor
```

# 3. Related Concept
## 3.1 Stencil Computation (SC)
Stencil computation sweeps over a spatial grid over multiple time steps to perform nearest-neighbor computations.

## 3.2 Compute Bound
Wiki: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CPU-bound. \
A computer is CPU-bound when the time for it to complete a task is determined principally by the speed of the centrl processor. \
Extension: In computer science, X-bound is the concept that performance is limited that can't be improved due to X.

## 3.3 Tranlation Look aside Buffer (TLB)
Memory instructions must go through a virtual-to-physical address translation, which is in the critical path of program execution. To improve translation speed, a TLB is used to cache virtual-to-physical translation of most frequently accessed pages. if the translation is not found in the TLB, processor pipeline stalls util the TLB miss is served.

## 3.4 Software Pipelining
Wiki: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Software_pipelining. \
Software pipelining is a technique used to optimize loops, it is a type of out-of-order execution.\
For example, consider the following loop:
```
for i = 1 to bignumber step 1
    A(i)
    B(i)
    C(i)
end
```
In this example, let A(i), B(i), C(i) be instructions, each operating on data i, that are dependent on each other: A(i) must complete before B(i) can start. For examples, A could load data from memory into a register, B could perform some arithmetic operation on the data, and C could store the data back into memory. However, let there be no dependence between operations for different values of i: A(2) can begin fefore A(1) finishes. \
Without software pipelining, the operations execute in the following sequence:
```
A(1) B(1) C(1) A(2) B(2) C(2) A(3) B(3) C(3) ...
```
Assume that each instruction takes 3 clock cycles to complete (ignore for the moment the cost of the looping control flow). Also assume that an instruction can be dispatched every cycle, as long as it has no dependencies on an instruction that is already executing. Inthe unpipelined case, each iteration thus takes 9 cycles to complete: 3 clock cycles for A(1), 3 clock cycles for B(1), and 3 clock cycles for C(1). \
Now consider the following sequence of instructions with software pipelining:
```
A(1) A(2) A(3) B(1) B(2) B(3) C(1) C(2) C(3) ...
```
It can be easily verified that an instruction can be dispatched each cycle, which means that the same 3 iterations can be executed in a total of 9 cycles, giving an average of 3 cycles per iteration. \
The implementation of software pipelining is showed below:
```
for i = 1 to (bignumber - 2) step 3
    A(i)
    A(i+1)
    A(i+2)
    B(i)
    B(i+1)
    B(i+2)
    C(i)
    C(i+1)
    C(i+2)
end
```

## 3.5 Thread-Level Parallelism (TLP)
Wiki: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Task_parallelism. \
Also known as Task Parallelism, is a form of parallelization of computer code across multiple processors in parallel computing enviroments. \
For example:
```
program:
...
if CPU="a" then
    do task "A"
else if CPU="b" then
    do task "B"
end if
...
end program
```
## 3.6 Data-Level Parallelism (DLP)
Wiki: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_parallelism. \
Also known as Data Parallelism, is parallelization across multiple processors in parallel computing enviroments. It focuses on distributing the data across different nodes, which operate on the data in parallel. \
In a multiprocessor system executing a single set of instructions (SIMD), data parallelism is achieved when each processor performs the same task on different pieces of distributed data. \
An example of DLP implemented using OpenMP is showed below:
```c
// Matrix multiplication in parallel
#pragma omp parallel for schedule(dynamic, 1) collapse(2)
for (i = 0; i < row_length_A; i++)
{
    for (k = 0; k < column_length_B; k++)
    {
        sum = 0;
        for (j = 0; j < column_length_A; j++)
        {
            sum += A[i][j] * B[j][k];
        }
        C[i][k] = sum;
    }
}
```
